04631nam a22005295i 9780804783217DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047832177 a10.1515/97808047832172doi  a(DE-B1597)564361  a(OCoLC)1198929591  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHM621b.N427 2012eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a149/.972231 aNealon, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPost-Postmodernism :bor, The Cultural Logic of Just-in-Time Capitalism /cJeffrey Nealon. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface: Why Post-Postmodernism? -- t1. Post-Postmodernism. Periodizing the '80s: The Cultural Logic of Economic Privatization in the US -- t2. Intensity. Empire of the Intensities: A Random Walk down Las Vegas Boulevard -- t3. Commodity. The Song Remains the Same: On the Post-Postmodern Economics of Classic Rock -- t4. University. The Associate Vice Provost in the Gray Flannel Suit: Administrative Labor and the Corporate University -- tInterruptive Excursus: Rereading. On the "Hermeneutics of Situation" in Nietzsche and Adorno -- t5. Deconstruction. Postdeconstructive? Negri, Derrida, and the Present State of Theory -- t6. Interpretation. The Swerve around P: Theory after Interpretation -- t7. Literature. Can Literature Be Equipment for Post-Postmodern Living -- tCoda: Liberal Arts. Not Your Father's Liberal Arts: or, Humanities Theory in the Post-Post Future -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPost-Postmodernism begins with a simple premise: we no longer live in the world of "postmodernism," famously dubbed "the cultural logic of late capitalism" by Fredric Jameson in 1984. Far from charting any simple move "beyond" postmodernism since the 1980s, though, this book argues that we've experienced an intensification of postmodern capitalism over the past decades, an increasing saturation of the economic sphere into formerly independent segments of everyday cultural life. If "fragmentation" was the preferred watchword of postmodern America, "intensification" is the dominant cultural logic of our contemporary era. Post-Postmodernism surveys a wide variety of cultural texts in pursuing its analyses-everything from the classic rock of Black Sabbath to the post-Marxism of Antonio Negri, from considerations of the corporate university to the fare at the cineplex, from reading experimental literature to gambling in Las Vegas, from Badiou to the undergraduate classroom. Insofar as cultural realms of all kinds have increasingly been overcoded by the languages and practices of economics, Nealon aims to construct a genealogy of the American present, and to build a vocabulary for understanding the relations between economic production and cultural production today-when American-style capitalism, despite its recent battering, seems nowhere near the point of obsolescence. Post-postmodern capitalism is seldom late but always just in time. As such, it requires an updated conceptual vocabulary for diagnosing and responding to our changed situation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCulturexEconomic aspects. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aPost-postmodernismxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aPost-postmodernismzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478321740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783217423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover